{"title":"Overload: Latency Attacks on Object Detection for Edge Devices","domain":"CV","seeds":[{"problem":"Existing adversarial attacks on object detectors largely target accuracy, or when targeting latency, rely on complex IoU-based objectives that are computationally and memory intensive—especially problematic on edge devices. The key open question is which model factors most effectively increase inference time with minimal attack cost.","method":"Overload analyzes NMS time complexity and shows latency is dominated by the number of objects fed into NMS rather than the number of surviving boxes. Based on this, it formulates a simple white-box objective that maximizes per-detection objectness confidence and class probabilities via a monotonic increasing function, inflating the number of pre-NMS objects without tracking pairwise IoUs. The attack is optimized with PGD-style updates under a small perturbation budget and is NMS-agnostic. Empirically, it generates >20k ghost objects and increases end-to-end latency by ~11–13× on Jetson NX, while using less memory/time than Daedalus and Phantom Sponge (e.g., ~3 min for 16 images at 7.5 GB vs. ~145 min for 10 images at 8.5 GB)."},{"problem":"Even with a strong objective, adversarial optimization can over-focus on regions already dense with detections, limiting the total number of ghost objects and thus the latency impact.","method":"Introduce spatial attention: tile the image into an m×m grid and adaptively weight each grid inversely to its current object density, so optimization emphasizes low-density regions. The weighted gradient step (PGD) is applied each iteration, continually updating grid weights from the detector’s intermediate outputs. This simple, gradient-free weighting boosts object counts by ~2,000+ over vanilla PGD and works best around a 5×5 grid, further increasing NMS load and latency."}]}
